snippet.textDisplay: @zetamaniac The story isn't the reason, but it is true that it was supposed to evolve (after marowak) into kangaskhan. The story is made up by someone, but the fact that the baby in the kangaskhan's pouch looks a lot like a baby cubone without the skull makes it very likely. Also, the size of kangaskhan makes sense for it to be a final evolution. It may have been changed due to the fact that every generation would wear it's mother's skull and have a skull over a skull?

snippet.textDisplay: When the game was first released in Japan, there was an odd phenomenon between children ages 7-12, particularly in those using headphones to listen to the sound effects. Increase of nosebleeds, irritability, insomnia, and addiction to the game, playing for hours and hours on end and crying to the point of vomitting when the opportunity was taken away. 70% of these cases ended in suicide.
snippet.textOriginal: When the game was first released in Japan, there was an odd phenomenon between children ages 7-12, particularly in those using headphones to listen to the sound effects. Increase of nosebleeds, irritability, insomnia, and addiction to the game, playing for hours and hours on end and crying to the point of vomitting when the opportunity was taken away. 70% of these cases ended in suicide.

snippet.textDisplay: In almost every case, despite game time hours recorded to the limit of the internal clock, the game had not progressed further than "Lavender Town".
snippet.textOriginal: In almost every case, despite game time hours recorded to the limit of the internal clock, the game had not progressed further than "Lavender Town".

snippet.textDisplay: A closer analysis of the game revealed a pitch of sound in the audio of the music for "Lavender Town" undetectable by fully developed human ear drums. Thousands of these "first edition" copies of the game (which conatin some other small differences) were recalled and the game was rereleased with remastered audio for "Lavender Town".
snippet.textOriginal: A closer analysis of the game revealed a pitch of sound in the audio of the music for "Lavender Town" undetectable by fully developed human ear drums. Thousands of these "first edition" copies of the game (which conatin some other small differences) were recalled and the game was rereleased with remastered audio for "Lavender Town".

snippet.textDisplay: The widely known version is said to be missing three extra notes, as well as the unique, binural pitch of the first edition, although this is uncomfirmed due to the rarity of working first edition copies; the internal clock and 'battery save' have all timed out and ceased fucntion, and in many cases the game will freeze upon entering any battle.
